{"title_page": "Linda Fairstein", "text_new": "{{short description|American author and former Assistant District Attorney}}\n{{Infobox writer \n|image = File:Linda Fairstein.jpg\n|imagesize =  |\n| name        = Linda Fairstein\n| caption     = Linda Fairstein (2009)\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1947|5|5}}\n| birth_place = [[Mount Vernon, New York]]<ref name = \"Lindsay\">{{cite book|last1=Lindsay|first1=Elizabeth Blakesley|title=Great Women Mystery Writers|date=2007|publisher=Greenwood Press|isbn=0-313-33428-5|pages=78|edition=2nd}}</ref>\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| occupation  = [[Novelist , racist]], former Assistant District Attorney and Head of Sex Crimes Unit of the County of New York\n| nationality = American\n| alma_mater       = \n[[Vassar College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>\n[[University of Virginia School of Law|University of Virginia]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n| spouses = {{marriage|Justin Feldman|1987|2011|end=died}}\n{{marriage|Michael Goldberg|2014}}\n| period      = 1996\u2013present\n| genre       = Crime\n| subject     = \n| movement    = \n|awards=\n*[[Federal Bar Council]]'s Emory Buckner Award for Public Service \n*[[UJA Federation]]\u2019s Proskauer Award\n*Columbia University School of Nursing's Second Century Award for Excellence in Health Care\n*''[[Glamour Magazine]]'''s Woman of the Year Award\n*[[American Heart Association]] Women of Courage Award\n*[[New York Women's Agenda]] 2010 Lifetime Achievement Award\n*[[Nero Wolfe Award]] for Excellence in Crime Writing (2008)\n*[[International Thriller Writers]] 2010 Silver Bullet Award<ref name=autogenerated2>[https://www.vassar.edu/trustees/bios/fairstein.html Linda Fairstein \u201969 - Board of Trustees - Vassar College<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n| signature   = \n| website = {{URL|lindafairstein.com}}\n| footnotes   = \n}}\n'''Linda Fairstein''' (born May 5, 1947) is an American author, attorney, and former New York City [[prosecutor]] focusing on crimes of violence against women and children. She was the head of the [[Sex and the law|sex crimes]] unit of the [[New York County District Attorney|Manhattan District Attorney]]'s office from 1976 until 2002. \n\nDuring that time, she oversaw the prosecution of the [[Central Park jogger case|Central Park Five case]], wherein five teenagers, four African-American and one Hispanic, were wrongfully convicted for the 1989 rape and assault in Central Park of a white female jogger. All five convictions were vacated in 2002 after Matias Reyes, a convicted serial rapist and murderer, confessed to having been the sole perpetrator of the crime, and DNA testing showed he was the sole contributor of the DNA of the semen on the victim. After Reyes's confession in 2002, Fairstein still maintained that the wrongfully convicted teenage boys were guilty and she lauded the police investigation as \"brilliant\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/culture-features/linda-fairstein-netflix-when-they-see-us-central-park-five-844864/|title=Who Is Linda Fairstein, the Prosecutor in \u2018When They See Us\u2019?|last=Dickson|first=E. J.|last2=Dickson|first2=E. J.|date=2019-06-07|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-08}}</ref> By 2018, she insisted that the teenagers' confessions had not been coerced.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.law.com/newyorklawjournal/2019/06/03/in-defense-of-the-central-park-5-prosecution/|title=In Defense of The Central Park 5 Prosecution|last=Fairstein|first=Linda |last2=|first2=|website=New York Law Journal|language=en|date=2019-06-03 |access-date=2019-06-08}}</ref>\n\nAfter she left the DA's office in 2002, Fairstein began to publish mystery novels featuring Manhattan prosecutor Alexandra Cooper.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.silive.com/women-of-achievement/2015/04/author_former_prosecutor_linda_fairstein_humbled_by_women_of_achievement_honorees.html|title=Author, former prosecutor Linda Fairstein 'humbled' by Women of Achievement honorees|work=SILive.com|access-date=2018-04-19|language=en-US}}</ref> Several have been bestsellers. In June 2019, after the release of the Netflix series ''[[When They See Us]]'' about the Central Park Five, Fairstein's publisher, [[Dutton Publishing|Dutton]], dropped her.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-48563756|title=Publisher drops Central Park Five prosecutor|date=2019-06-08|access-date=2019-06-08|work= BBC News|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nFairstein graduated with honors from [[Vassar College]] in 1969, with a degree in [[English literature]]. She graduated from the [[University of Virginia School of Law]] in 1972, where she was one of a dozen women in her class.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n== Legal career ==\nFairstein joined the [[Manhattan District Attorney]]'s office in 1972 as an [[Assistant District Attorney]]. In 1976 she was promoted to the head of the [[sex crimes unit]], where she worked to support victims of crime.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news |first=Katherine |last=Bouton |title=Linda Fairstein vs. Rape |date=1990-02-25 |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C0CE1DE1739F936A15751C0A966958260 |work=The New York Times Magazine |access-date=2008-01-23}}</ref> During her tenure, she prosecuted controversial and highly publicized cases, such as the \"Preppy Murder case\" against [[Robert Chambers (criminal)|Robert Chambers]] in 1986, and the 1998 ''[[People v. Jovanovic]]'' cases.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/09/28/lawsuit-over-sex-arrest-is-dismissed/|title=Lawsuit Over Sex Arrest Is Dismissed|last=Zraick|first=Karen|date=2010-09-28|website=City Room|language=en-US|access-date=2018-04-19}}</ref> \n\nFairstein, as Head of Sex Crimes, oversaw the prosecution of five juvenile defendants known as the \"Central Park Five\" in the 1989 \"[[Central Park Jogger]]\" case. The case was prosecuted by ADAs Elizabeth Lederer and Arthur Clements, with trials held in 1990.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/08/03/nyregion/father-defends-his-son-at-central-park-trial.html|title=Father Defends His Son At Central Park Trial|last=Sullivan|first=Ronald|access-date=2018-04-19|language=en}}</ref> The convictions in the case were [[vacate]]d in 2002 following a confession by the perpetrator, a convicted serial rapist and murderer, and confirmation by a [[DNA]] match to evidence at the scene.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/nation/nationnow/la-na-nn-central-park-five-jogger-20140627-story.html|title=Central Park Five: Money was not the issue in settlement with NYC|last=Susman|first=Tina|website=latimes.com|access-date=2018-04-19}}</ref> \n\nFairstein left the District Attorney's office in 2002, and has continued to consult, write, lecture and serve as a sex crimes expert for a wide variety of print and television media outlets, including [[CNN]], [[MSNBC]] and [[Larry King]], among others. She has consulted for a number of media outlets during a number of high-profile prosecutions, including [[Michael Jackson]]'s molestation charges in 2004,<ref>{{cite news |title=Michael Jackson Arraigned |date=2004-04-30 |work=The Washington Post |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A56664-2004Apr30.html |access-date=2008-01-23 | first=Linda | last=Fairstein}}</ref> [[Kobe Bryant]]'s sexual assault charges,<ref>{{cite news |title=American Morning |date=2003-12-19 |publisher=CNN |url=http://edition.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0312/19/ltm.03.html |access-date=2008-01-23}}</ref> and [[Scott Peterson]]'s trial.<ref>{{cite news |title=American Morning |date=2003-12-25 |publisher=CNN |url=http://edition.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0312/25/ltm.10.html |accessdate=2008-01-23}}</ref> \n\nShe was also reportedly involved with a defense of [[Harvey Weinstein]], helping to silence one of the sexual harassment complaints against him.<ref>{{Cite AV media|title='Times' Reporters Describe How A Paper Trail Helped Break The Weinstein Story|date=November 15, 2017|first=Terry|last=Gross|work=NPR Fresh Air|quote=\u2026There was this Italian model who showed up to the Weinstein Co. for a business meeting with Harvey Weinstein. And within hours of leaving, she went to the police department here in New York and said that he had groped her and that she was willing to make a police complaint about it. \u2026there was a whole team that swooped in to help Harvey Weinstein fight that in a counterattack effort. There were private investigators who were dispatched to basically dig up dirt on her. There were stories planted in the tabloids to basically disparage her background. There were high-profile attorneys who stepped up to Harvey's side, including Linda Fairstein, the former sex crimes prosecutor here in Manhattan, (with Cyrus Vance) who was willing to facilitate introductions to the current sex crimes prosecutor who was handling the case. And within weeks that case was dead.  |url=https://www.npr.org/2017/11/15/564310240/times-reporters-describe-how-a-paper-trail-helped-break-the-weinstein-story}}</ref> \n\nFairstein founded the Domestic Violence Committee of the [[New York Women's Agenda]]. She is a frequent speaker on issues related to [[domestic abuse]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Jennifer |last=Connic |date=2006-10-22 |title=Fairstein Addresses Issues of Domestic Violence |url=http://www.westportnow.com/index.php?/v2/comments/15011/ |work=Westport Now |accessdate=2008-01-23}}</ref>\n\n=== Central Park Jogger case ===\n\n==== Investigation, conviction and appeal ====\nFairstein's office supervised the prosecution in 1989 and 1990 of the [[Central Park Jogger case]], which ended in the conviction of five teenagers<ref name = \"exonerated\">{{cite news | first=Benjamin | last=Weiser | date=June 19, 2014  | title=5 Exonerated in Central Park Jogger Case Will Settle Suit for $40 Million | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/06/20/nyregion/5-exonerated-in-central-park-jogger-case-are-to-settle-suit-for-40-million.html | work = The New York Times }}</ref> whose convictions were later [[vacate]]d. In a civil rights lawsuit filed in 2003, the five who were convicted claimed that Fairstein, with the assistance of the detectives at the 20th Precinct, coerced false confessions from them following up to thirty straight hours of interrogation and intimidation, of both the youths and their supporting adults.<ref name = \"ashblond\" />  When Assistant US attorney David Nocenti, a \"[[Big Brothers Big Sisters of New York City|Big Brother]]\" mentor to Yusef Salaam, one of the defendants, appeared at the precinct while the defendant was being grilled, plaintiffs claimed, Fairstein verbally abused him, demanded he leave immediately, and called her husband to demand the home number of Nocenti's boss, Brooklyn [[US Attorney]] Andrew Maloney, so she could get the young attorney fired.<ref name=\"ashblond\" /><ref name=\"Sullivan1992\">{{cite book|author=Timothy John Sullivan|title=Unequal Verdicts: the Central Park jogger trials|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5d48AQAAIAAJ|date=November 1992|publisher=American Lawyer Books/Simon & Schuster|isbn=978-0-671-74237-9}}</ref>{{page needed|date=June 2019}}\n\nFairstein said \"Nobody under sixteen was talked to until a parent or guardian arrived... Three of the five went home and had a night's sleep before they were ever taken into custody. For most of them, the substance of their admissions came out within about an hour of the time they came in... I think Reyes ran with that pack of kids. He stayed longer when the others moved on. He completed the assault. I don't think there is a question in the minds of anyone present during the interrogation process that these five men were participants, not only in the other attacks that night but in the attack on the jogger. I watched more than thirty detectives\u2014black, white, Hispanic guys who'd never met each other before\u2014conduct a brilliant investigation.\"<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite magazine|first=Jeffrey |last=Toobin|date=November 24, 2002|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2002/12/02/a-prosecutor-speaks-up |title=A Prosecutor Speaks Up  |work=The New Yorker}}</ref> Lawyers for the five defendants contested almost every element of Fairstein's statement.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> \n\nAll five accused teenagers later claimed their confessions were coerced during interrogation through lies and intimidation.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Schanberg |first1=Sydney |title=A Journey Through the Tangled Case of the Central Park Jogger |url=http://www.villagevoice.com/news/0247,schanberg,39999,1.html |access-date=2009-04-25 |publisher=Village Voice |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080621201511/http://www.villagevoice.com/news/0247%2Cschanberg%2C39999%2C1.html |archivedate=2008-06-21 }}</ref> In 1990 each of the \"Central Park Five\" were convicted of various assault and sexual battery charges, based in part on the allegedly [[false confession]]s obtained from them in 1989.<ref name = \"exonerated\" /> Antron McCray, Kevin Richardson, Raymond Santana and Korey Wise had signed written confessions, while Yousef Salaam made a verbal confession but refused to sign.<ref name = \"ashblond\" /> \n\nTheir convictions were upheld on appeal. Appellate court judge Vito Titone specifically named Fairstein in his dissenting opinion on the Salaam appeal. He said in an interview, \"I was concerned about a criminal justice system that would tolerate the conduct of the prosecutor, Linda Fairstein, who deliberately engineered the 15-year-old's confession. ... Fairstein wanted to make a name. She didn't care. She wasn't a human.\"<ref name = \"ashblond\">{{cite news|last1=Little|first1=Rivka Gewirtz|title=Ash-Blond Ambition Prosecutor Linda Fairstein May Have Tried Too Hard|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2002-11-19/news/ash-blond-ambition/2/|publisher=Village Voice|date=November 19, 2002}}</ref>\n\n==== Vacating of convictions ====\nAll five convictions were vacated in 2002 after convicted rapist Matias Reyes confessed to the crime.<ref name=\"Saulny\">{{cite news |first=Susan |last=Saulny |title=Convictions and Charges Voided In '89 Central Park Jogger Attack |work=[[New York Times]] |date=2002-12-20 |quote=''Thirteen years after an investment banker jogging in Central Park was savagely beaten, raped and left for dead, a Manhattan judge threw out the convictions yesterday of the five young men who had confessed to attacking the woman on a night of violence that stunned the city and the nation.''}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Saulny|first1=Susan|title=Convictions and Charges Voided In '89 Central Park Jogger Attack|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/12/20/nyregion/convictions-and-charges-voided-in-89-central-park-jogger-attack.html|publisher=New York Times|accessdate=22 April 2017}}</ref><ref>[http://www.law.com/jsp/article.jsp?id=1039054478324 Central Park Jogger Convictions Vacated] Law.com.</ref> Reyes confessed after he \"found religion.\"<ref name=\":4\" /> The police had recovered DNA of only one man at the site of the crime, and none of the Central Park Five matched. The [[semen]] found on the victim contained DNA matching that of Reyes, confirming that he was the sole contributor, to a certainty of six billion to one.<ref name=\"Morgenthau\">{{cite web|url=http://www.manhattanda.org/whatsnew/press/2002-12-05a.pdf |title=Affirmation in Response to Motion to Vacate Judgment of Conviction: The People of the State of New York -against- Kharey Wise, Kevin Richardson, Antron McCray, Yusef Salaam, and Raymond Santana, Defendants |date=2002-12-05 |format=PDF |publisher=[[Robert M. Morgenthau]], [[District Attorney]], [[New York County]] |access-date=2007-06-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070629221224/http://www.manhattanda.org/whatsnew/press/2002-12-05a.pdf |archivedate=2007-06-29 }}</ref>\n\n==== Aftermath ====\nIn 2003, Kevin Richardson, Raymond Santana Jr., and Antron McCray sued the city of New York for [[malicious prosecution]], [[racism|racial discrimination]] and [[Intentional infliction of emotional distress|emotional distress]].<ref>{{cite web | first=Glyn | last=Vincent | date=July 7, 2009 | title=Ken Burns Illuminates Jogger Case | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/glyn-vincent/central-park-jogger-hiidd_b_226670.html | publisher = Huffington Post }}</ref> While the city refused to settle for 11 years, upon Mayor De Blasio taking office a settlement in the case was reached on June 19, 2014, for $41 million.<ref name=\"exonerated\" />\n\n[[Ken Burns]] and his daughter Sarah and her husband made a documentary film about the case, which he compared to the [[Scottsboro Boys]] case.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/13/arts/television/13jens.html | first=Elizabeth | last=Jensen | date=2009-09-10 | access-date=2012-12-04 | work=The New York Times | title=Ken Burns, the Voice of the Wilderness }}</ref> The film, ''[[The Central Park Five]]'', premiered at the [[Cannes Film Festival]] in May 2012 and was released on November 23, 2012.\n\nIn May 2019, [[Netflix]] released a four-part drama series, ''[[When They See Us]]'', about the case, directed by [[Ava DuVernay]].  In it, actress [[Felicity Huffman]] portrays Fairstein.  Soon after the release, Fairstein's publisher, [[E. P. Dutton|E.P. Dutton]], released her as a client.<ref name=\":4\" />  Fairstein was also forced to resign from various non-profit board roles, including [[Safe Horizon]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.esquire.com/entertainment/tv/a27749297/linda-fairstein-central-park-five-prosecutor-when-they-see-us-backlash/|title=Central Park Five Prosecutor Linda Fairstein Has Responded to When They See Us Backlash|last=Storey|first=Kate|date=2019-06-05|website=Esquire|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-07}}</ref> Fairstein also resigned from the Board of Trustees of Vassar College, her alma mater, after considerable pressure from the student body and members of the administration.<ref>https://www.poughkeepsiejournal.com/story/news/education/2019/06/04/linda-fairstein-central-park-five-case-resigns-vassar/1345650001/</ref> \n\nOn June 10, 2019, the ''[[The Wall Street Journal|Wall Street Journal]]'' published an [[op-ed]] by Fairstein, ''Netflix\u2019s False Story of the Central Park Five,'' in which she says that five were not \"totally innocent\" (citing the other crimes they were convicted for, for which, she asserts, there is still substantial evidence) and that DuVernay had [[Defamation|defamed]] her.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/netflixs-false-story-of-the-central-park-five-11560207823|title=Opinion {{!}} Netflix\u2019s False Story of the Central Park Five|last=Fairstein|first=Linda|date=2019-06-10|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2019-06-12|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/11/arts/television/linda-fairstein-when-they-see-us.html|title=Linda Fairstein Attacks Her Portrayal in \u2018When They See Us\u2019|last=Harris|first=Elizabeth A.|date=2019-06-11|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-06-13|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In March 2020, Fairstein filed suit in the [[U.S. District Court for the Middle District of Florida]] against Netflix, DuVernay, and series writer [[Attica Locke]] for [[defamation]] based on her portrayal in the series.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Moghe |first1=Sonia |title='When They See Us' creators sued for defamation by former prosecutor |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/18/entertainment/linda-fairstein-suit/index.html |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=CNN |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Faughnder |first1=Ryan |title=She was the villain in 'When They See Us.' Now she's suing Ava DuVernay and Netflix |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/business/story/2020-03-18/linda-fairstein-central-park-five-was-the-villain-in-when-they-see-us-now-shes-suing-netflix-ava-duvernay |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=Los Angeles Times |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Jovanovic controversy ===\n[[Oliver Jovanovic]] sued Fairstein, alleging that she engaged in \"false arrest, [[malicious prosecution]], malicious abuse of process and denial of his right to a fair trial\".<ref>http://www.websupp.org/data/SDNY/1:04-cv-08437-39-SDNY.pdf.{{dead link|date=June 2019}}</ref> This lawsuit stemmed from Fairstein's successful prosecution of Jovanovic in the case ''[[People v. Jovanovic]]'', which was subsequently overturned on appeal.<ref>[http://www.anusha.com/jov-deci.htm Decision of Supreme Court, Appellate Division, December 1999], including summary of all relevant facts</ref> It was dismissed [[prejudice (law)|with prejudice]] by a new trial judge. The dismissal was requested \"in the interest of justice\" by the office of the Manhattan district attorney, [[Robert M. Morgenthau]].<ref>[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E03E3DC1E30F931A35752C1A9679C8B63 Charges Dismissed in Columbia Sexual Torture Case], ''[[The New York Times]]'', November 2, 2001.</ref>\n\nThere was no physical evidence linking Jovanovic to the crime. While his accuser claimed she had been brutally attacked and left bleeding, she was found to have only a few fading bruises. \"If she [Fairstein] couldn't tell this was a false report, well, I am just shocked,\" said former New York City sex crimes detective John Baeza, who worked in defense of Jovanovic after leaving the force.<ref name=ashblond />\n\nThe $10 million lawsuit against Fairstein and two co-defendants, former Manhattan Assistant District Attorney Gail Heatherly, who now teaches at the [[Columbia Law School]], and New York City Police Detective Milton Bonilla, was dismissed on [[summary judgment]] in September 2010.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hamblett|first=Mark|title=Court Throws Out Civil Rights Suit Filed After Dismissal of 'Cybersex Torture' Charges|url=http://www.law.com/jsp/article.jsp?id=1202472669187&Court_Throws_Out_Civil_Rights_Lawsuit_Filed_After_Dismissal_of_Cybersex_Torture_Charges|work=Law.com|publisher=ALM|accessdate=30 September 2010}}</ref>\n\n=== Dominique Strauss-Kahn ===\nFairstein assisted District Attorney Vance in his decision not to prosecute [[Dominique Strauss-Kahn]] for sexual assault in 2012. Fairstein's writing skills came into play in writing up the decision not to charge.<ref name=\"Solomon2012\">{{cite book|author=John Solomon|title=DSK: The Scandal That Brought Down Dominique Strauss-Kahn|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rscsNAnBhXUC|date=5 June 2012|publisher=St. Martin's Press|isbn=978-1-250-01264-7}}</ref>\n\n=== Awards ===\nAmong the awards Fairstein has received are the [[Federal Bar Council]]'s Emory Buckner Award for Public Service, ''[[Glamour Magazine]]'''s Woman of the Year Award, and the [[Nero Wolfe Award]] for Excellence in Crime Writing.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\" /> \n\nIn 2018, the [[Mystery Writers of America]] announced that it would honor Fairstein with one of its \"Grand Master\" awards for literary achievement. But two days after renewed controversy erupted in connection with her role in the case, the organization withdrew the honor.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/11/28/nyregion/linda-fairstein-central-park-5.html|title=After Furor, Literary Group Withdraws Honor for \u2018Central Park Five\u2019 Prosecutor|last1=Piccoli|first1=Sean|date=November 28, 2018|newspaper=The New York Times|access-date=28 December 2018|last2=Gold|first2=Michael}}</ref> In 2019, shortly after the release of the Netflix series ''When They See Us'' about the Central Park Five case, ''Glamour Magazine'' said that the 1993 Woman of the Year Award to Fairstein was a mistake and that it was given to her before the full facts of the case were known.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.glamour.com/story/a-note-on-linda-fairstein-1993-woman-of-the-year-award|title=A Note on Linda Fairstein's 1993 Woman of the Year Award|last=Nast|first=Cond\u00e9|website=Glamour|language=en|access-date=2019-06-07}}</ref>\n\n==Writing career==\n=== Alexandra Cooper series ===\n[[File:Linda Fairstein (4037658814).jpg|alt=Linda Fairstein, Recipient of the 2003 Royden B. Davis Distinguished Author Award|thumb|Linda Fairstein at the [[University of Scranton]] 2003 Royden B. Davis Distinguished Author Award presentation.]]\nFairstein has written several crime novels featuring Manhattan prosecutor Alexandra Cooper. The novels draw on Fairstein's legal expertise and several have become international best sellers.<ref>{{cite news |first=Stuart |last=Jeffries |title=The Rapist Hunter |date=2004-02-27 |work=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/g2/story/0,3604,1157234,00.html |accessdate=2008-01-23 | location=London}}</ref>\n\nThe titles are:\n\n* ''Final Jeopardy'' (1996)<ref name = \"Lindsay\" />\n* ''Likely To Die'' (1997)<ref name = \"Lindsay\" />\n* ''Cold Hit'' (1999)<ref name = \"Lindsay\" />\n* ''The Dead-House'' (2001)<ref name = \"Lindsay\" /> ([[Nero Award]] winner)\n* ''The Bone Vault'' (2003)<ref name = \"Lindsay\" />\n* ''The Kills'' (2004)<ref name = \"Lindsay\" />\n* ''Entombed'' (2005)<ref name = \"Lindsay\" />\n* ''Death Dance'' (2006)<ref name = \"Lindsay\" />\n* ''Bad Blood'' (2007)<ref name=\"Husbands\">{{cite book|author1=Janet Husband|author2=Jonathan F. Husband|title=Sequels: An Annotated Guide to Novels in Series|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tBUlCAwAtNwC&pg=PA186|year=2009|publisher=American Library Association|isbn=978-0-8389-0967-6|pages=186\u2013}}</ref>\n* ''Killer Heat'' (2008)<ref name=\"Husbands\"/>\n* ''Lethal Legacy'' (2009)<ref>{{cite web|title = Lethal Legacy Review |url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/linda-fairstein/lethal-legacy/|publisher=Kirkus Reviews|date=February 10, 2009}}</ref>\n* ''Hell Gate'' (2010)<ref name = \"Kirkus\">{{cite web|title=Linda Fairstein|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/search/?q=Linda%20Fairstein;t=author|publisher=Kirkus Reviews|accessdate=20 June 2014}}</ref>\n* ''Silent Mercy'' (March 2011)<ref name = \"Kirkus\" />\n* ''Night Watch'' (July 2012)<ref name = \"Kirkus\" />\n* ''Death Angel'' (2013)<ref name = \"Kirkus\" />\n* ''Terminal City'' (2014)<ref name = \"Kirkus\" />\n* ''Devil's Bridge'' (2015)<ref>{{cite web|title=Amazon listing|url=https://www.amazon.com/Devils-Bridge-Alexandra-Cooper-Fairstein/dp/0525953892/ref=asap_bc?ie=UTF8}}</ref>\n* ''Killer Look'' (2016)<ref>{{cite web|title=Killer Look|url=http://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/531608/killer-look-by-linda-fairstein/9781101984031/|website=Penguin Random House|publisher=Penguin Random House|accessdate=16 July 2017}}</ref>\n* ''Deadfall'' (2017)\n* ''Blood Oath'' (2019)\n\n=== Devlin Quick series ===\n*''Into the Lion's Den'' (2016)\n*''Digging for Trouble'' (2017)\n*''Secrets from the Deep'' (2018)\n\n=== Nonfiction ===\n* ''Sexual Violence: Our War Against Rape'' (1993)<ref name = \"Lindsay\" /><ref name = \"Kirkus\" />\n\n==Awards==\n{{More citations needed section|date=June 2019}}\nAmong her awards are the:\n\n*[[Federal Bar Council]]'s Emory Buckner Award for Public Service \n*[[UJA Federation]]\u2019s Proskauer Award\n*Columbia University School of Nursing's Second Century Award for Excellence in Health Care<ref>{{cite magazine\n| author     =<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> \n| date       = 2001\n| title      = The Academic Nurse\n| journal    = The Journal of the Columbia University School of Nursing\n| volume     = 18\n| issue      = 2\n| pages      = 3\n| access-date= \n}}</ref>\n*''[[Glamour Magazine]]'''s Woman of the Year Award (rescinded in 2019)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.glamour.com/story/a-note-on-linda-fairstein-1993-woman-of-the-year-award|title=A Note on Linda Fairstein's 1993 Woman of the Year Award|last=Nast|first=Cond\u00e9|website=Glamour|language=en|access-date=2019-06-07}}</ref>\n\n*[[American Heart Association]] Women of Courage Award\n*[[New York Women's Agenda]] 2010 Lifetime Achievement Award\n*[[Nero Wolfe Award]] for Excellence in Crime Writing (2008)\n*[[International Thriller Writers]] 2010 Silver Bullet Award<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\n== Personal life ==\nFairstein grew up in [[Mount Vernon, New York|Mount Vernon]], New York.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/09/12/arts/design/linda-fairstein-prosecutor-sex-crimes.html|title=Linda Fairstein Looks Crime in the Face and Smiles|last=Shattuck|first=Kathryn|date=2017-09-12|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-04-19|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Her father's family were [[Russian Jews]] who immigrated in the early 1900s. Her mother is of Northern Irish, Finnish and Swedish descent.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.lilith.org/blog/2017/01/this-groundbreaking-lawyer-turned-novelist-has-just-published-a-new-series/ |title=This Groundbreaking Lawyer-Turned-Novelist Has Just Published a New Series |date=January 13, 2017 |author=Yona Zeldis McDonough |work=[[Lilith (magazine)|Lilith]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170313072607/https://www.lilith.org/blog/2017/01/this-groundbreaking-lawyer-turned-novelist-has-just-published-a-new-series/ |archivedate=2017-03-13}}</ref> She was married to lawyer Justin Feldman from 1987 until his death in 2011 at the age of 92.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/25/nyregion/justin-n-feldman-92-dies-opposed-tammany-hall.html|title=Justin N. Feldman, 92, Dies; Opposed Tammany Hall|last=Grimes|first=William|date=2011-09-24|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-04-19|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/27/realestate/the-case-of-the-disappearing-chintz.html|title=The Case of the Disappearing Chintz|last=Kaufman|first=Joanne|date=2014-04-24|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-04-19|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In September 2014 she married lawyer Michael Goldberg, a long-time friend and classmate at the University of Virginia School of Law, at their home in [[Martha's Vineyard]]. Fairstein and Goldberg reside in the [[Upper East Side]] in New York.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://lindafairstein.com Alex Cooper Crime Novels]\n* [http://mostlyfiction.com/authorqa/fairstein.html mostlyfiction.com interview with Linda Fairstein, author of Lethal Legacy]\n* [http://www.makers.com/linda-fairstein Linda Fairstein]  Video produced by ''[[Makers: Women Who Make America]]''\n* [http://www.cbsnews.com/videos/crime-author-linda-fairstein/ CBS News Sunday Morning interview with Linda Fairstein broadcast July 16, 2017]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fairstein, Linda}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Vassar College alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Virginia School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:American Jews]]\n[[Category:Jewish feminists]]\n[[Category:American prosecutors]]\n[[Category:American crime fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Nero Award winners]]\n[[Category:American women lawyers]]\n[[Category:American feminists]]\n[[Category:American women novelists]]\n[[Category:Writers from Mount Vernon, New York]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Women mystery writers]]\n[[Category:Novelists from New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American author and former Assistant District Attorney}}\n{{Infobox writer \n|image = File:Linda Fairstein.jpg\n|imagesize =  |\n| name        = Linda Fairstein\n| caption     = Linda Fairstein (2009)\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1947|5|5}}\n| birth_place = [[Mount Vernon, New York]]<ref name = \"Lindsay\">{{cite book|last1=Lindsay|first1=Elizabeth Blakesley|title=Great Women Mystery Writers|date=2007|publisher=Greenwood Press|isbn=0-313-33428-5|pages=78|edition=2nd}}</ref>\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| occupation  = [[Novelist]], former Assistant District Attorney and Head of Sex Crimes Unit of the County of New York\n| nationality = American\n| alma_mater       = \n[[Vassar College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>\n[[University of Virginia School of Law|University of Virginia]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n| spouses = {{marriage|Justin Feldman|1987|2011|end=died}}\n{{marriage|Michael Goldberg|2014}}\n| period      = 1996\u2013present\n| genre       = Crime\n| subject     = \n| movement    = \n|awards=\n*[[Federal Bar Council]]'s Emory Buckner Award for Public Service \n*[[UJA Federation]]\u2019s Proskauer Award\n*Columbia University School of Nursing's Second Century Award for Excellence in Health Care\n*''[[Glamour Magazine]]'''s Woman of the Year Award\n*[[American Heart Association]] Women of Courage Award\n*[[New York Women's Agenda]] 2010 Lifetime Achievement Award\n*[[Nero Wolfe Award]] for Excellence in Crime Writing (2008)\n*[[International Thriller Writers]] 2010 Silver Bullet Award<ref name=autogenerated2>[https://www.vassar.edu/trustees/bios/fairstein.html Linda Fairstein \u201969 - Board of Trustees - Vassar College<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n| signature   = \n| website = {{URL|lindafairstein.com}}\n| footnotes   = \n}}\n'''Linda Fairstein''' (born May 5, 1947) is an American author, attorney, and former New York City [[prosecutor]] focusing on crimes of violence against women and children. She was the head of the [[Sex and the law|sex crimes]] unit of the [[New York County District Attorney|Manhattan District Attorney]]'s office from 1976 until 2002. \n\nDuring that time, she oversaw the prosecution of the [[Central Park jogger case|Central Park Five case]], wherein five teenagers, four African-American and one Hispanic, were wrongfully convicted for the 1989 rape and assault in Central Park of a white female jogger. All five convictions were vacated in 2002 after Matias Reyes, a convicted serial rapist and murderer, confessed to having been the sole perpetrator of the crime, and DNA testing showed he was the sole contributor of the DNA of the semen on the victim. After Reyes's confession in 2002, Fairstein still maintained that the wrongfully convicted teenage boys were guilty and she lauded the police investigation as \"brilliant\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/culture-features/linda-fairstein-netflix-when-they-see-us-central-park-five-844864/|title=Who Is Linda Fairstein, the Prosecutor in \u2018When They See Us\u2019?|last=Dickson|first=E. J.|last2=Dickson|first2=E. J.|date=2019-06-07|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-08}}</ref> By 2018, she insisted that the teenagers' confessions had not been coerced.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.law.com/newyorklawjournal/2019/06/03/in-defense-of-the-central-park-5-prosecution/|title=In Defense of The Central Park 5 Prosecution|last=Fairstein|first=Linda |last2=|first2=|website=New York Law Journal|language=en|date=2019-06-03 |access-date=2019-06-08}}</ref>\n\nAfter she left the DA's office in 2002, Fairstein began to publish mystery novels featuring Manhattan prosecutor Alexandra Cooper.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.silive.com/women-of-achievement/2015/04/author_former_prosecutor_linda_fairstein_humbled_by_women_of_achievement_honorees.html|title=Author, former prosecutor Linda Fairstein 'humbled' by Women of Achievement honorees|work=SILive.com|access-date=2018-04-19|language=en-US}}</ref> Several have been bestsellers. In June 2019, after the release of the Netflix series ''[[When They See Us]]'' about the Central Park Five, Fairstein's publisher, [[Dutton Publishing|Dutton]], dropped her.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-48563756|title=Publisher drops Central Park Five prosecutor|date=2019-06-08|access-date=2019-06-08|work= BBC News|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nFairstein graduated with honors from [[Vassar College]] in 1969, with a degree in [[English literature]]. She graduated from the [[University of Virginia School of Law]] in 1972, where she was one of a dozen women in her class.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n== Legal career ==\nFairstein joined the [[Manhattan District Attorney]]'s office in 1972 as an [[Assistant District Attorney]]. In 1976 she was promoted to the head of the [[sex crimes unit]], where she worked to support victims of crime.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news |first=Katherine |last=Bouton |title=Linda Fairstein vs. Rape |date=1990-02-25 |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C0CE1DE1739F936A15751C0A966958260 |work=The New York Times Magazine |access-date=2008-01-23}}</ref> During her tenure, she prosecuted controversial and highly publicized cases, such as the \"Preppy Murder case\" against [[Robert Chambers (criminal)|Robert Chambers]] in 1986, and the 1998 ''[[People v. Jovanovic]]'' cases.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/09/28/lawsuit-over-sex-arrest-is-dismissed/|title=Lawsuit Over Sex Arrest Is Dismissed|last=Zraick|first=Karen|date=2010-09-28|website=City Room|language=en-US|access-date=2018-04-19}}</ref> \n\nFairstein, as Head of Sex Crimes, oversaw the prosecution of five juvenile defendants known as the \"Central Park Five\" in the 1989 \"[[Central Park Jogger]]\" case. The case was prosecuted by ADAs Elizabeth Lederer and Arthur Clements, with trials held in 1990.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/08/03/nyregion/father-defends-his-son-at-central-park-trial.html|title=Father Defends His Son At Central Park Trial|last=Sullivan|first=Ronald|access-date=2018-04-19|language=en}}</ref> The convictions in the case were [[vacate]]d in 2002 following a confession by the perpetrator, a convicted serial rapist and murderer, and confirmation by a [[DNA]] match to evidence at the scene.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/nation/nationnow/la-na-nn-central-park-five-jogger-20140627-story.html|title=Central Park Five: Money was not the issue in settlement with NYC|last=Susman|first=Tina|website=latimes.com|access-date=2018-04-19}}</ref> \n\nFairstein left the District Attorney's office in 2002, and has continued to consult, write, lecture and serve as a sex crimes expert for a wide variety of print and television media outlets, including [[CNN]], [[MSNBC]] and [[Larry King]], among others. She has consulted for a number of media outlets during a number of high-profile prosecutions, including [[Michael Jackson]]'s molestation charges in 2004,<ref>{{cite news |title=Michael Jackson Arraigned |date=2004-04-30 |work=The Washington Post |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A56664-2004Apr30.html |access-date=2008-01-23 | first=Linda | last=Fairstein}}</ref> [[Kobe Bryant]]'s sexual assault charges,<ref>{{cite news |title=American Morning |date=2003-12-19 |publisher=CNN |url=http://edition.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0312/19/ltm.03.html |access-date=2008-01-23}}</ref> and [[Scott Peterson]]'s trial.<ref>{{cite news |title=American Morning |date=2003-12-25 |publisher=CNN |url=http://edition.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0312/25/ltm.10.html |accessdate=2008-01-23}}</ref> \n\nShe was also reportedly involved with a defense of [[Harvey Weinstein]], helping to silence one of the sexual harassment complaints against him.<ref>{{Cite AV media|title='Times' Reporters Describe How A Paper Trail Helped Break The Weinstein Story|date=November 15, 2017|first=Terry|last=Gross|work=NPR Fresh Air|quote=\u2026There was this Italian model who showed up to the Weinstein Co. for a business meeting with Harvey Weinstein. And within hours of leaving, she went to the police department here in New York and said that he had groped her and that she was willing to make a police complaint about it. \u2026there was a whole team that swooped in to help Harvey Weinstein fight that in a counterattack effort. There were private investigators who were dispatched to basically dig up dirt on her. There were stories planted in the tabloids to basically disparage her background. There were high-profile attorneys who stepped up to Harvey's side, including Linda Fairstein, the former sex crimes prosecutor here in Manhattan, (with Cyrus Vance) who was willing to facilitate introductions to the current sex crimes prosecutor who was handling the case. And within weeks that case was dead.  |url=https://www.npr.org/2017/11/15/564310240/times-reporters-describe-how-a-paper-trail-helped-break-the-weinstein-story}}</ref> \n\nFairstein founded the Domestic Violence Committee of the [[New York Women's Agenda]]. She is a frequent speaker on issues related to [[domestic abuse]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Jennifer |last=Connic |date=2006-10-22 |title=Fairstein Addresses Issues of Domestic Violence |url=http://www.westportnow.com/index.php?/v2/comments/15011/ |work=Westport Now |accessdate=2008-01-23}}</ref>\n\n=== Central Park Jogger case ===\n\n==== Investigation, conviction and appeal ====\nFairstein's office supervised the prosecution in 1989 and 1990 of the [[Central Park Jogger case]], which ended in the conviction of five teenagers<ref name = \"exonerated\">{{cite news | first=Benjamin | last=Weiser | date=June 19, 2014  | title=5 Exonerated in Central Park Jogger Case Will Settle Suit for $40 Million | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/06/20/nyregion/5-exonerated-in-central-park-jogger-case-are-to-settle-suit-for-40-million.html | work = The New York Times }}</ref> whose convictions were later [[vacate]]d. In a civil rights lawsuit filed in 2003, the five who were convicted claimed that Fairstein, with the assistance of the detectives at the 20th Precinct, coerced false confessions from them following up to thirty straight hours of interrogation and intimidation, of both the youths and their supporting adults.<ref name = \"ashblond\" />  When Assistant US attorney David Nocenti, a \"[[Big Brothers Big Sisters of New York City|Big Brother]]\" mentor to Yusef Salaam, one of the defendants, appeared at the precinct while the defendant was being grilled, plaintiffs claimed, Fairstein verbally abused him, demanded he leave immediately, and called her husband to demand the home number of Nocenti's boss, Brooklyn [[US Attorney]] Andrew Maloney, so she could get the young attorney fired.<ref name=\"ashblond\" /><ref name=\"Sullivan1992\">{{cite book|author=Timothy John Sullivan|title=Unequal Verdicts: the Central Park jogger trials|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5d48AQAAIAAJ|date=November 1992|publisher=American Lawyer Books/Simon & Schuster|isbn=978-0-671-74237-9}}</ref>{{page needed|date=June 2019}}\n\nFairstein said \"Nobody under sixteen was talked to until a parent or guardian arrived... Three of the five went home and had a night's sleep before they were ever taken into custody. For most of them, the substance of their admissions came out within about an hour of the time they came in... I think Reyes ran with that pack of kids. He stayed longer when the others moved on. He completed the assault. I don't think there is a question in the minds of anyone present during the interrogation process that these five men were participants, not only in the other attacks that night but in the attack on the jogger. I watched more than thirty detectives\u2014black, white, Hispanic guys who'd never met each other before\u2014conduct a brilliant investigation.\"<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite magazine|first=Jeffrey |last=Toobin|date=November 24, 2002|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2002/12/02/a-prosecutor-speaks-up |title=A Prosecutor Speaks Up  |work=The New Yorker}}</ref> Lawyers for the five defendants contested almost every element of Fairstein's statement.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> \n\nAll five accused teenagers later claimed their confessions were coerced during interrogation through lies and intimidation.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Schanberg |first1=Sydney |title=A Journey Through the Tangled Case of the Central Park Jogger |url=http://www.villagevoice.com/news/0247,schanberg,39999,1.html |access-date=2009-04-25 |publisher=Village Voice |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080621201511/http://www.villagevoice.com/news/0247%2Cschanberg%2C39999%2C1.html |archivedate=2008-06-21 }}</ref> In 1990 each of the \"Central Park Five\" were convicted of various assault and sexual battery charges, based in part on the allegedly [[false confession]]s obtained from them in 1989.<ref name = \"exonerated\" /> Antron McCray, Kevin Richardson, Raymond Santana and Korey Wise had signed written confessions, while Yousef Salaam made a verbal confession but refused to sign.<ref name = \"ashblond\" /> \n\nTheir convictions were upheld on appeal. Appellate court judge Vito Titone specifically named Fairstein in his dissenting opinion on the Salaam appeal. He said in an interview, \"I was concerned about a criminal justice system that would tolerate the conduct of the prosecutor, Linda Fairstein, who deliberately engineered the 15-year-old's confession. ... Fairstein wanted to make a name. She didn't care. She wasn't a human.\"<ref name = \"ashblond\">{{cite news|last1=Little|first1=Rivka Gewirtz|title=Ash-Blond Ambition Prosecutor Linda Fairstein May Have Tried Too Hard|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2002-11-19/news/ash-blond-ambition/2/|publisher=Village Voice|date=November 19, 2002}}</ref>\n\n==== Vacating of convictions ====\nAll five convictions were vacated in 2002 after convicted rapist Matias Reyes confessed to the crime.<ref name=\"Saulny\">{{cite news |first=Susan |last=Saulny |title=Convictions and Charges Voided In '89 Central Park Jogger Attack |work=[[New York Times]] |date=2002-12-20 |quote=''Thirteen years after an investment banker jogging in Central Park was savagely beaten, raped and left for dead, a Manhattan judge threw out the convictions yesterday of the five young men who had confessed to attacking the woman on a night of violence that stunned the city and the nation.''}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Saulny|first1=Susan|title=Convictions and Charges Voided In '89 Central Park Jogger Attack|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/12/20/nyregion/convictions-and-charges-voided-in-89-central-park-jogger-attack.html|publisher=New York Times|accessdate=22 April 2017}}</ref><ref>[http://www.law.com/jsp/article.jsp?id=1039054478324 Central Park Jogger Convictions Vacated] Law.com.</ref> Reyes confessed after he \"found religion.\"<ref name=\":4\" /> The police had recovered DNA of only one man at the site of the crime, and none of the Central Park Five matched. The [[semen]] found on the victim contained DNA matching that of Reyes, confirming that he was the sole contributor, to a certainty of six billion to one.<ref name=\"Morgenthau\">{{cite web|url=http://www.manhattanda.org/whatsnew/press/2002-12-05a.pdf |title=Affirmation in Response to Motion to Vacate Judgment of Conviction: The People of the State of New York -against- Kharey Wise, Kevin Richardson, Antron McCray, Yusef Salaam, and Raymond Santana, Defendants |date=2002-12-05 |format=PDF |publisher=[[Robert M. Morgenthau]], [[District Attorney]], [[New York County]] |access-date=2007-06-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070629221224/http://www.manhattanda.org/whatsnew/press/2002-12-05a.pdf |archivedate=2007-06-29 }}</ref>\n\n==== Aftermath ====\nIn 2003, Kevin Richardson, Raymond Santana Jr., and Antron McCray sued the city of New York for [[malicious prosecution]], [[racism|racial discrimination]] and [[Intentional infliction of emotional distress|emotional distress]].<ref>{{cite web | first=Glyn | last=Vincent | date=July 7, 2009 | title=Ken Burns Illuminates Jogger Case | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/glyn-vincent/central-park-jogger-hiidd_b_226670.html | publisher = Huffington Post }}</ref> While the city refused to settle for 11 years, upon Mayor De Blasio taking office a settlement in the case was reached on June 19, 2014, for $41 million.<ref name=\"exonerated\" />\n\n[[Ken Burns]] and his daughter Sarah and her husband made a documentary film about the case, which he compared to the [[Scottsboro Boys]] case.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/13/arts/television/13jens.html | first=Elizabeth | last=Jensen | date=2009-09-10 | access-date=2012-12-04 | work=The New York Times | title=Ken Burns, the Voice of the Wilderness }}</ref> The film, ''[[The Central Park Five]]'', premiered at the [[Cannes Film Festival]] in May 2012 and was released on November 23, 2012.\n\nIn May 2019, [[Netflix]] released a four-part drama series, ''[[When They See Us]]'', about the case, directed by [[Ava DuVernay]].  In it, actress [[Felicity Huffman]] portrays Fairstein.  Soon after the release, Fairstein's publisher, [[E. P. Dutton|E.P. Dutton]], released her as a client.<ref name=\":4\" />  Fairstein was also forced to resign from various non-profit board roles, including [[Safe Horizon]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.esquire.com/entertainment/tv/a27749297/linda-fairstein-central-park-five-prosecutor-when-they-see-us-backlash/|title=Central Park Five Prosecutor Linda Fairstein Has Responded to When They See Us Backlash|last=Storey|first=Kate|date=2019-06-05|website=Esquire|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-07}}</ref> Fairstein also resigned from the Board of Trustees of Vassar College, her alma mater, after considerable pressure from the student body and members of the administration.<ref>https://www.poughkeepsiejournal.com/story/news/education/2019/06/04/linda-fairstein-central-park-five-case-resigns-vassar/1345650001/</ref> \n\nOn June 10, 2019, the ''[[The Wall Street Journal|Wall Street Journal]]'' published an [[op-ed]] by Fairstein, ''Netflix\u2019s False Story of the Central Park Five,'' in which she says that five were not \"totally innocent\" (citing the other crimes they were convicted for, for which, she asserts, there is still substantial evidence) and that DuVernay had [[Defamation|defamed]] her.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/netflixs-false-story-of-the-central-park-five-11560207823|title=Opinion {{!}} Netflix\u2019s False Story of the Central Park Five|last=Fairstein|first=Linda|date=2019-06-10|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2019-06-12|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/11/arts/television/linda-fairstein-when-they-see-us.html|title=Linda Fairstein Attacks Her Portrayal in \u2018When They See Us\u2019|last=Harris|first=Elizabeth A.|date=2019-06-11|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-06-13|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In March 2020, Fairstein filed suit in the [[U.S. District Court for the Middle District of Florida]] against Netflix, DuVernay, and series writer [[Attica Locke]] for [[defamation]] based on her portrayal in the series.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Moghe |first1=Sonia |title='When They See Us' creators sued for defamation by former prosecutor |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/18/entertainment/linda-fairstein-suit/index.html |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=CNN |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Faughnder |first1=Ryan |title=She was the villain in 'When They See Us.' Now she's suing Ava DuVernay and Netflix |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/business/story/2020-03-18/linda-fairstein-central-park-five-was-the-villain-in-when-they-see-us-now-shes-suing-netflix-ava-duvernay |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=Los Angeles Times |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Jovanovic controversy ===\n[[Oliver Jovanovic]] sued Fairstein, alleging that she engaged in \"false arrest, [[malicious prosecution]], malicious abuse of process and denial of his right to a fair trial\".<ref>http://www.websupp.org/data/SDNY/1:04-cv-08437-39-SDNY.pdf.{{dead link|date=June 2019}}</ref> This lawsuit stemmed from Fairstein's successful prosecution of Jovanovic in the case ''[[People v. Jovanovic]]'', which was subsequently overturned on appeal.<ref>[http://www.anusha.com/jov-deci.htm Decision of Supreme Court, Appellate Division, December 1999], including summary of all relevant facts</ref> It was dismissed [[prejudice (law)|with prejudice]] by a new trial judge. The dismissal was requested \"in the interest of justice\" by the office of the Manhattan district attorney, [[Robert M. Morgenthau]].<ref>[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E03E3DC1E30F931A35752C1A9679C8B63 Charges Dismissed in Columbia Sexual Torture Case], ''[[The New York Times]]'', November 2, 2001.</ref>\n\nThere was no physical evidence linking Jovanovic to the crime. While his accuser claimed she had been brutally attacked and left bleeding, she was found to have only a few fading bruises. \"If she [Fairstein] couldn't tell this was a false report, well, I am just shocked,\" said former New York City sex crimes detective John Baeza, who worked in defense of Jovanovic after leaving the force.<ref name=ashblond />\n\nThe $10 million lawsuit against Fairstein and two co-defendants, former Manhattan Assistant District Attorney Gail Heatherly, who now teaches at the [[Columbia Law School]], and New York City Police Detective Milton Bonilla, was dismissed on [[summary judgment]] in September 2010.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hamblett|first=Mark|title=Court Throws Out Civil Rights Suit Filed After Dismissal of 'Cybersex Torture' Charges|url=http://www.law.com/jsp/article.jsp?id=1202472669187&Court_Throws_Out_Civil_Rights_Lawsuit_Filed_After_Dismissal_of_Cybersex_Torture_Charges|work=Law.com|publisher=ALM|accessdate=30 September 2010}}</ref>\n\n=== Dominique Strauss-Kahn ===\nFairstein assisted District Attorney Vance in his decision not to prosecute [[Dominique Strauss-Kahn]] for sexual assault in 2012. Fairstein's writing skills came into play in writing up the decision not to charge.<ref name=\"Solomon2012\">{{cite book|author=John Solomon|title=DSK: The Scandal That Brought Down Dominique Strauss-Kahn|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rscsNAnBhXUC|date=5 June 2012|publisher=St. Martin's Press|isbn=978-1-250-01264-7}}</ref>\n\n=== Awards ===\nAmong the awards Fairstein has received are the [[Federal Bar Council]]'s Emory Buckner Award for Public Service, ''[[Glamour Magazine]]'''s Woman of the Year Award, and the [[Nero Wolfe Award]] for Excellence in Crime Writing.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\" /> \n\nIn 2018, the [[Mystery Writers of America]] announced that it would honor Fairstein with one of its \"Grand Master\" awards for literary achievement. But two days after renewed controversy erupted in connection with her role in the case, the organization withdrew the honor.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/11/28/nyregion/linda-fairstein-central-park-5.html|title=After Furor, Literary Group Withdraws Honor for \u2018Central Park Five\u2019 Prosecutor|last1=Piccoli|first1=Sean|date=November 28, 2018|newspaper=The New York Times|access-date=28 December 2018|last2=Gold|first2=Michael}}</ref> In 2019, shortly after the release of the Netflix series ''When They See Us'' about the Central Park Five case, ''Glamour Magazine'' said that the 1993 Woman of the Year Award to Fairstein was a mistake and that it was given to her before the full facts of the case were known.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.glamour.com/story/a-note-on-linda-fairstein-1993-woman-of-the-year-award|title=A Note on Linda Fairstein's 1993 Woman of the Year Award|last=Nast|first=Cond\u00e9|website=Glamour|language=en|access-date=2019-06-07}}</ref>\n\n==Writing career==\n=== Alexandra Cooper series ===\n[[File:Linda Fairstein (4037658814).jpg|alt=Linda Fairstein, Recipient of the 2003 Royden B. Davis Distinguished Author Award|thumb|Linda Fairstein at the [[University of Scranton]] 2003 Royden B. Davis Distinguished Author Award presentation.]]\nFairstein has written several crime novels featuring Manhattan prosecutor Alexandra Cooper. The novels draw on Fairstein's legal expertise and several have become international best sellers.<ref>{{cite news |first=Stuart |last=Jeffries |title=The Rapist Hunter |date=2004-02-27 |work=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/g2/story/0,3604,1157234,00.html |accessdate=2008-01-23 | location=London}}</ref>\n\nThe titles are:\n\n* ''Final Jeopardy'' (1996)<ref name = \"Lindsay\" />\n* ''Likely To Die'' (1997)<ref name = \"Lindsay\" />\n* ''Cold Hit'' (1999)<ref name = \"Lindsay\" />\n* ''The Dead-House'' (2001)<ref name = \"Lindsay\" /> ([[Nero Award]] winner)\n* ''The Bone Vault'' (2003)<ref name = \"Lindsay\" />\n* ''The Kills'' (2004)<ref name = \"Lindsay\" />\n* ''Entombed'' (2005)<ref name = \"Lindsay\" />\n* ''Death Dance'' (2006)<ref name = \"Lindsay\" />\n* ''Bad Blood'' (2007)<ref name=\"Husbands\">{{cite book|author1=Janet Husband|author2=Jonathan F. Husband|title=Sequels: An Annotated Guide to Novels in Series|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tBUlCAwAtNwC&pg=PA186|year=2009|publisher=American Library Association|isbn=978-0-8389-0967-6|pages=186\u2013}}</ref>\n* ''Killer Heat'' (2008)<ref name=\"Husbands\"/>\n* ''Lethal Legacy'' (2009)<ref>{{cite web|title = Lethal Legacy Review |url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/linda-fairstein/lethal-legacy/|publisher=Kirkus Reviews|date=February 10, 2009}}</ref>\n* ''Hell Gate'' (2010)<ref name = \"Kirkus\">{{cite web|title=Linda Fairstein|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/search/?q=Linda%20Fairstein;t=author|publisher=Kirkus Reviews|accessdate=20 June 2014}}</ref>\n* ''Silent Mercy'' (March 2011)<ref name = \"Kirkus\" />\n* ''Night Watch'' (July 2012)<ref name = \"Kirkus\" />\n* ''Death Angel'' (2013)<ref name = \"Kirkus\" />\n* ''Terminal City'' (2014)<ref name = \"Kirkus\" />\n* ''Devil's Bridge'' (2015)<ref>{{cite web|title=Amazon listing|url=https://www.amazon.com/Devils-Bridge-Alexandra-Cooper-Fairstein/dp/0525953892/ref=asap_bc?ie=UTF8}}</ref>\n* ''Killer Look'' (2016)<ref>{{cite web|title=Killer Look|url=http://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/531608/killer-look-by-linda-fairstein/9781101984031/|website=Penguin Random House|publisher=Penguin Random House|accessdate=16 July 2017}}</ref>\n* ''Deadfall'' (2017)\n* ''Blood Oath'' (2019)\n\n=== Devlin Quick series ===\n*''Into the Lion's Den'' (2016)\n*''Digging for Trouble'' (2017)\n*''Secrets from the Deep'' (2018)\n\n=== Nonfiction ===\n* ''Sexual Violence: Our War Against Rape'' (1993)<ref name = \"Lindsay\" /><ref name = \"Kirkus\" />\n\n==Awards==\n{{More citations needed section|date=June 2019}}\nAmong her awards are the:\n\n*[[Federal Bar Council]]'s Emory Buckner Award for Public Service \n*[[UJA Federation]]\u2019s Proskauer Award\n*Columbia University School of Nursing's Second Century Award for Excellence in Health Care<ref>{{cite magazine\n| author     =<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> \n| date       = 2001\n| title      = The Academic Nurse\n| journal    = The Journal of the Columbia University School of Nursing\n| volume     = 18\n| issue      = 2\n| pages      = 3\n| access-date= \n}}</ref>\n*''[[Glamour Magazine]]'''s Woman of the Year Award (rescinded in 2019)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.glamour.com/story/a-note-on-linda-fairstein-1993-woman-of-the-year-award|title=A Note on Linda Fairstein's 1993 Woman of the Year Award|last=Nast|first=Cond\u00e9|website=Glamour|language=en|access-date=2019-06-07}}</ref>\n\n*[[American Heart Association]] Women of Courage Award\n*[[New York Women's Agenda]] 2010 Lifetime Achievement Award\n*[[Nero Wolfe Award]] for Excellence in Crime Writing (2008)\n*[[International Thriller Writers]] 2010 Silver Bullet Award<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\n== Personal life ==\nFairstein grew up in [[Mount Vernon, New York|Mount Vernon]], New York.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/09/12/arts/design/linda-fairstein-prosecutor-sex-crimes.html|title=Linda Fairstein Looks Crime in the Face and Smiles|last=Shattuck|first=Kathryn|date=2017-09-12|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-04-19|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Her father's family were [[Russian Jews]] who immigrated in the early 1900s. Her mother is of Northern Irish, Finnish and Swedish descent.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.lilith.org/blog/2017/01/this-groundbreaking-lawyer-turned-novelist-has-just-published-a-new-series/ |title=This Groundbreaking Lawyer-Turned-Novelist Has Just Published a New Series |date=January 13, 2017 |author=Yona Zeldis McDonough |work=[[Lilith (magazine)|Lilith]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170313072607/https://www.lilith.org/blog/2017/01/this-groundbreaking-lawyer-turned-novelist-has-just-published-a-new-series/ |archivedate=2017-03-13}}</ref> She was married to lawyer Justin Feldman from 1987 until his death in 2011 at the age of 92.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/25/nyregion/justin-n-feldman-92-dies-opposed-tammany-hall.html|title=Justin N. Feldman, 92, Dies; Opposed Tammany Hall|last=Grimes|first=William|date=2011-09-24|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-04-19|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/27/realestate/the-case-of-the-disappearing-chintz.html|title=The Case of the Disappearing Chintz|last=Kaufman|first=Joanne|date=2014-04-24|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-04-19|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In September 2014 she married lawyer Michael Goldberg, a long-time friend and classmate at the University of Virginia School of Law, at their home in [[Martha's Vineyard]]. Fairstein and Goldberg reside in the [[Upper East Side]] in New York.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://lindafairstein.com Alex Cooper Crime Novels]\n* [http://mostlyfiction.com/authorqa/fairstein.html mostlyfiction.com interview with Linda Fairstein, author of Lethal Legacy]\n* [http://www.makers.com/linda-fairstein Linda Fairstein]  Video produced by ''[[Makers: Women Who Make America]]''\n* [http://www.cbsnews.com/videos/crime-author-linda-fairstein/ CBS News Sunday Morning interview with Linda Fairstein broadcast July 16, 2017]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fairstein, Linda}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Vassar College alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Virginia School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:American Jews]]\n[[Category:Jewish feminists]]\n[[Category:American prosecutors]]\n[[Category:American crime fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Nero Award winners]]\n[[Category:American women lawyers]]\n[[Category:American feminists]]\n[[Category:American women novelists]]\n[[Category:Writers from Mount Vernon, New York]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Women mystery writers]]\n[[Category:Novelists from New York (state)]]\n", "name_user": "189.4.73.144", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Showing what white people do to black people)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linda_Fairstein"}
{"title_page": "National emblem of Turkey", "text_new": "{{Infobox coat of arms\n|name             = National Emblem of the <br> Republic of Turkey\n|image            = Emblem of Turkey.svg\n|image_width      = 250\n|middle           = \n|middle_width     = \n|middle_caption   = \n|lesser           = \n|lesser_width     = \n|lesser_caption   = \n|image2           = \n|image2_width     =\n|image2_caption   = \n|image3           = \n|image3_width     = \n|image3_caption   = \n|armiger          = [[Turkey|Republic of Turkey]]\n|year_adopted     = \n|crest            = \n|torse            = \n|shield           = [[Star and crescent|Crescent and star]]\n|supporters       = \n|compartment      = \n|motto            = \n|orders           =\n|other_elements   = \n|earlier_versions =\n|use              = [[Turkish passport]], [[Turkish ID card]], [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Turkey)]]\n}}\n[[File:Botschaft 021.jpg|thumbnail|The emblem of Turkey, seen at the [[List of diplomatic missions of Turkey|Turkish Embassy]] in [[Vienna]], [[Austria]].]]\n[[File:TurkeyPassport.jpg|thumb|The emblem on Turkish passports]]\n[[File:TR Nat ID Card Front.png|thumb|The emblem on national ID cards]]\n\n[[Turkey]] has no official national emblem, but the [[star and crescent|crescent and star]] ({{lang-tr|ay-y\u0131ld\u0131z}} \"crescent-star\") design from the [[Flag of Turkey|national flag]] is in use as ''de facto'' emblem, among other things printed on  [[Turkish passport]]s, on [[Turkish identity card]]s and [[diplomatic missions of Turkey]].\n\nThe crescent and star is retained from the 19th-century [[Ottoman flag]], and has acquired its status as de facto national emblem following the abolition of the  [[Coat of arms of the Ottoman Empire|Ottoman coat of arms]] in 1922. It was used on national identity cards by the 1930s (with the horns of the crescent facing left instead of the now more common orientation towards the right).\n\n== Use by government bodies ==\n\n=== Red circle with white star and crescent ===\nA circular section of the red [[Flag of Turkey]] containing the white crescent and star is used in the current emblems of a number of Turkish ministries and governmental institutions, in the emblem of the [[Grand National Assembly of Turkey|Grand National Assembly]], and as the flag badge on the uniforms of Turkish national sports teams and athletes. It was also used on the old (non-digital) Turkish identity cards.<ref>[http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/4/46/Republic_of_Turkey_ID_card.gif Specimen of the old (non-digital) Turkish identity card]{{dead link|date=February 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Turkey Emblem.png|Circular emblem used as a badge by the national sports teams, as well as for other semi-official purposes\nFile:Seal of the Turkish Parliament (T\u00fcrkiye B\u00fcy\u00fck Millet Meclisi).svg|Seal of the Grand National Assembly (parliament)\n</gallery>\n\n=== Gold circle with white star and crescent ===\n\n=== Coat of arms of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs ===\n[[File:Turkse ambassade, Den Haag.JPG|thumb|[[List of diplomatic missions of Turkey|Turkish Embassy]] in [[The Hague]], [[Netherlands]], with the [[Oval (geometry)|oval]]-shaped ambassadorial [[escutcheon (heraldry)|escutcheon]] which is derived from the oval [[shield]] at the center of the [[Coat of arms of the Ottoman Empire|Ottoman coat of arms]].]]\n\nThe [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Turkey)|Turkish Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] often uses a red [[Oval (geometry)|oval]]-shaped [[escutcheon (heraldry)|escutcheon]] which takes its colour from the Turkish flag, while its shape echoes the oval [[shield]] at the center of the late 19th-century [[Coat of arms of the Ottoman Empire|Ottoman coat of arms]].<ref>[http://www.mfa.gov.tr/default.en.mfa Web site of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Republic of Turkey]</ref> The escutcheon contains a [[gold (color)|gold-tone]] crescent and star which are vertically oriented (with the star on top) and surrounded by the gold-tone text ''T.C. D\u0131\u015fi\u015fleri Bakanl\u0131\u011f\u0131''.<ref>[http://www.memurum.biz/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/d%C4%B1%C5%9Fi%C5%9Fleri.png Official escutcheon of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Republic of Turkey]</ref> A variant of this oval escutcheon (containing the gold-tone text ''T\u00fcrkiye Cumhuriyeti B\u00fcy\u00fckel\u00e7ili\u011fi'') is used by the Turkish embassies.<ref>[http://www.ukrturk.net/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/kiev-b%C3%BCy%C3%BCkel%C3%A7ili%C4%9Fi.jpg Official escutcheon of the Turkish Embassies] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130126012818/http://www.ukrturk.net/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/kiev-b%C3%BCy%C3%BCkel%C3%A7ili%C4%9Fi.jpg |date=2013-01-26 }}</ref><ref>[http://2.bp.blogspot.com/_w6NK9TTlXDc/TPZw-NEmAHI/AAAAAAAAAnI/M1H4aI8QCMQ/s1600/b3dfe14616_b.jpg Official escutcheon of the Turkish Embassies]</ref>\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Disisleri-bakanligi-logo.png|Variant used by the Ministry of Foreign Affairs\nFile:Tc buyukelcilikamblem.svg|Escutcheon used by the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, [[List of diplomatic missions of Turkey|Embassies]]\nFile:TC Consulate\u2013General Emblem.svg|Escutcheon used by the [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Turkey|Ministry of Foreign Affairs]], [[List of diplomatic missions of Turkey|Consulates]]\n</gallery>\n\n=== Presidential seal ===\nThe [[Presidential Seal of Turkey|seal of the President of Turkey]] has a large 16-pointed star in the center, which is surrounded by 16 five-pointed stars, symbolizing the [[16 Great Turkic Empires]].<ref>[http://www.tccb.gov.tr/sayfa/cumhurbaskanligi/fors/ Official website of the Turkish Presidency: Detailed description of the Turkish Presidential Seal]</ref> Its appearance is regulated by law.\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Emblem of the President of Turkey.png|Presidential Seal of Turkey\nFile:Flag of the President of Turkey.svg|Presidential Flag of Turkey\n</gallery>\n\n==Proposed coat of arms==\nIn 1925, the [[Ministry of National Education (Turkey)|Ministry of National Education]] held a contest for a national emblem. [[Nam\u0131k \u0130smail]], a painter, won the contest with his coat of arms depicting [[Asena]], a mythological [[wolf]] in the [[Myth of origins#Founding myth|founding myth]] of the ''G\u00f6kb\u00f6r\u00fc'' clan which ruled the [[G\u00f6kt\u00fcrks|G\u00f6kt\u00fcrk Empire]]. However, this coat of arms was never used.\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Insigne Turciae.svg|Nam\u0131k \u0130smail's winning coat of arms ([[:File:1925arma.gif|rendition]])\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Turkey|Heraldry}}\n* [[Coat of arms of the Ottoman Empire]]\n* [[Flag of Turkey]]\n* [[Turkey]]\n* [[Coats of arms of Europe]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Heraldry by country}}\n{{Coats of arms of Europe}}\n{{Coats of arms of Asia}}\n{{Turkey topics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Emblems Of Turkey}}\n[[Category:National emblems|Turkey]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Turkey]]\n[[Category:Heraldry by country|Turkey]]\n[[Category:Coats of arms with the star and crescent|Turkey]]\n[[Category:Turkish coats of arms]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox coat of arms\n|name             = National Emblem of the <br> Republic of Turkey\n|image            = Emblem of Turkey.svg\n|image_width      = 250\n|middle           = \n|middle_width     = \n|middle_caption   = \n|lesser           = \n|lesser_width     = \n|lesser_caption   = \n|image2           = \n|image2_width     =\n|image2_caption   = \n|image3           = \n|image3_width     = \n|image3_caption   = \n|armiger          = [[Turkey|Republic of Turkey]]\n|year_adopted     = \n|crest            = \n|torse            = \n|shield           = [[Star and crescent|Crescent and star]]\n|supporters       = \n|compartment      = \n|motto            = \n|orders           =\n|other_elements   = \n|earlier_versions =\n|use              = [[Turkish passport]], [[Turkish ID card]], [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Turkey)]]\n}}\n[[File:Botschaft 021.jpg|thumbnail|The emblem of Turkey, seen at the [[List of diplomatic missions of Turkey|Turkish Embassy]] in [[Vienna]], [[Austria]].]]\n[[File:TurkeyPassport.jpg|thumb|The emblem on Turkish passports]]\n[[File:TR Nat ID Card Front.png|thumb|The emblem on national ID cards]]\n\n[[Turkey]] has no official national emblem, but the [[star and crescent|crescent and star]] ({{lang-tr|ay-y\u0131ld\u0131z}} \"crescent-star\") design from the [[Flag of Turkey|national flag]] is in use as ''de facto'' emblem, among other things printed on  [[Turkish passport]]s, on [[Turkish identity card]]s and [[diplomatic missions of Turkey]].\n\nThe crescent and star is retained from the 19th-century [[Ottoman flag]], and has acquired its status as de facto national emblem following the abolition of the  [[Coat of arms of the Ottoman Empire|Ottoman coat of arms]] in 1922. It was used on national identity cards by the 1930s (with the horns of the crescent facing left instead of the now more common orientation towards the right).\n\n== Use by government bodies ==\n\n=== Red circle with white star and crescent ===\nA circular section of the red [[Flag of Turkey]] containing the white crescent and star is used in the current emblems of a number of Turkish ministries and governmental institutions, in the emblem of the [[Grand National Assembly of Turkey|Grand National Assembly]], and as the flag badge on the uniforms of Turkish national sports teams and athletes. It was also used on the old (non-digital) Turkish identity cards.<ref>[http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/4/46/Republic_of_Turkey_ID_card.gif Specimen of the old (non-digital) Turkish identity card]{{dead link|date=February 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Turkey Emblem.png|Circular emblem used as a badge by the national sports teams, as well as for other semi-official purposes\nFile:Seal of the Turkish Parliament (T\u00fcrkiye B\u00fcy\u00fck Millet Meclisi).svg|Seal of the Grand National Assembly (parliament)\n</gallery>\n\n=== Gold circle with white star and crescent ===\n\n=== Coat of arms of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs ===\n[[File:Turkse ambassade, Den Haag.JPG|thumb|[[List of diplomatic missions of Turkey|Turkish Embassy]] in [[The Hague]], [[Netherlands]], with the [[Oval (geometry)|oval]]-shaped ambassadorial [[escutcheon (heraldry)|escutcheon]] which is derived from the oval [[shield]] at the center of the [[Coat of arms of the Ottoman Empire|Ottoman coat of arms]].]]\n\nThe [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Turkey)|Turkish Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] often uses a red [[Oval (geometry)|oval]]-shaped [[escutcheon (heraldry)|escutcheon]] which takes its colour from the Turkish flag, while its shape echoes the oval [[shield]] at the center of the late 19th-century [[Coat of arms of the Ottoman Empire|Ottoman coat of arms]].<ref>[http://www.mfa.gov.tr/default.en.mfa Web site of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Republic of Turkey]</ref> The escutcheon contains a [[gold (color)|gold-tone]] crescent and star which are vertically oriented (with the star on top) and surrounded by the gold-tone text ''T.C. D\u0131\u015fi\u015fleri Bakanl\u0131\u011f\u0131''.<ref>[http://www.memurum.biz/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/d%C4%B1%C5%9Fi%C5%9Fleri.png Official escutcheon of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Republic of Turkey]</ref> A variant of this oval escutcheon (containing the gold-tone text ''T\u00fcrkiye Cumhuriyeti B\u00fcy\u00fckel\u00e7ili\u011fi'') is used by the Turkish embassies.<ref>[http://www.ukrturk.net/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/kiev-b%C3%BCy%C3%BCkel%C3%A7ili%C4%9Fi.jpg Official escutcheon of the Turkish Embassies] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130126012818/http://www.ukrturk.net/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/kiev-b%C3%BCy%C3%BCkel%C3%A7ili%C4%9Fi.jpg |date=2013-01-26 }}</ref><ref>[http://2.bp.blogspot.com/_w6NK9TTlXDc/TPZw-NEmAHI/AAAAAAAAAnI/M1H4aI8QCMQ/s1600/b3dfe14616_b.jpg Official escutcheon of the Turkish Embassies]</ref>\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Emblem of the Republic of Turkey.svg|Escutcheon used by the [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Turkey|Ministry of Foreign Affairs]], [[List of diplomatic missions of Turkey|Embassies and Consulates]]\nFile:Disisleri-bakanligi-logo.png|Variant used by the Ministry of Foreign Affairs\n</gallery>\n\n=== Presidential seal ===\nThe [[Presidential Seal of Turkey|seal of the President of Turkey]] has a large 16-pointed star in the center, which is surrounded by 16 five-pointed stars, symbolizing the [[16 Great Turkic Empires]].<ref>[http://www.tccb.gov.tr/sayfa/cumhurbaskanligi/fors/ Official website of the Turkish Presidency: Detailed description of the Turkish Presidential Seal]</ref> Its appearance is regulated by law.\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Emblem of the President of Turkey.png|Presidential Seal of Turkey\nFile:Flag of the President of Turkey.svg|Presidential Flag of Turkey\n</gallery>\n\n==Proposed coat of arms==\nIn 1925, the [[Ministry of National Education (Turkey)|Ministry of National Education]] held a contest for a national emblem. [[Nam\u0131k \u0130smail]], a painter, won the contest with his coat of arms depicting [[Asena]], a mythological [[wolf]] in the [[Myth of origins#Founding myth|founding myth]] of the ''G\u00f6kb\u00f6r\u00fc'' clan which ruled the [[G\u00f6kt\u00fcrks|G\u00f6kt\u00fcrk Empire]]. However, this coat of arms was never used.\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Insigne Turciae.svg|Nam\u0131k \u0130smail's winning coat of arms ([[:File:1925arma.gif|rendition]])\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Turkey|Heraldry}}\n* [[Coat of arms of the Ottoman Empire]]\n* [[Flag of Turkey]]\n* [[Turkey]]\n* [[Coats of arms of Europe]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Heraldry by country}}\n{{Coats of arms of Europe}}\n{{Coats of arms of Asia}}\n{{Turkey topics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Emblems Of Turkey}}\n[[Category:National emblems|Turkey]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Turkey]]\n[[Category:Heraldry by country|Turkey]]\n[[Category:Coats of arms with the star and crescent|Turkey]]\n[[Category:Turkish coats of arms]]\n", "name_user": "Jelican9", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCoat of arms of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_emblem_of_Turkey"}
{"title_page": "Batwoman (TV series)", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date=October 2019}}\n{{short description|2019 American superhero television series}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Batwoman\n| image                    = Batwoman TV series logo.png\n| caption                  = \n| alt                      = \n| genre                    = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Superhero fiction|Superhero]]\n* [[Drama]]\n* [[Crime fiction|Crime]]\n* [[Mystery fiction|Mystery]]\n}}\n| based_on                 = {{based on|[[Batwoman]]||[[Geoff Johns]]|[[Grant Morrison]]|[[Greg Rucka]]|[[Mark Waid]]|[[Keith Giffen]]}}\n| developer                = [[Caroline Dries]]\n| composer                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Blake Neely]]\n* Sherri Chung\n}}\n| starring                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Ruby Rose]]\n* [[Rachel Skarsten]]\n* [[Meagan Tandy]]\n* Nicole Kang\n* Camrus Johnson\n* Elizabeth Anweis\n* [[Dougray Scott]]\n<!--Starring cast order is according to original broadcasting credits (the pilot episode). Do NOT rearrange cast order, per MOS:TVCAST. In addition, new starring cast members will be at the bottom of the list.-->\n}}\n| country                  = United States\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = 1<!--Only increment as a new season premieres, per the documentation of the template!-->\n| num_episodes             = 16<!--Only increment as a new episode premieres, per the documentation of the template!-->\n| list_episodes            = #Episodes\n| executive_producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Caroline Dries\n* [[Greg Berlanti]]\n* Sarah Schechter\n* [[Geoff Johns]]\n* [[David Nutter]]\n* [[Marcos Siega]]\n* [[Marc Guggenheim]]\n}}\n| producer                 = \n| location                 =\n{{Plainlist|\n* [[Vancouver, British Columbia]]\n* [[Chicago, Illinois]]\n}}\n| cinematography           = \n| editor                   = \n| camera                   = [[Single-camera setup|Single-camera]]\n| runtime                  = 42\u201343 minutes\n| channel                  = [[The CW]]\n| picture_format           = [[High-definition television|HDTV]] [[1080i]]\n| audio_format             = [[Dolby Digital]] 5.1\n| company                  = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Greg Berlanti|Berlanti Productions]]\n* [[DC Comics|DC Entertainment]]\n* [[Warner Bros. Television]]\n}}\n| distributor              = [[Warner Bros. Television Distribution]]\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2019|10|6}}\n| last_aired               = {{End date|present}}\n| related                  = [[Arrowverse]]\n| website_title            = \n| production_website       = \n}}\n\n'''''Batwoman''''' is an American [[Superhero fiction|superhero]] television series developed by [[Caroline Dries]]. It is based on the [[DC Comics]] character [[Batwoman]], a costumed crime-fighter created by [[Geoff Johns]], [[Grant Morrison]], [[Greg Rucka]], [[Mark Waid]], and [[Keith Giffen]], and is set in the [[Arrowverse]], sharing continuity with the other television series of the universe. The series premiered on [[The CW]] on October 6, 2019 and is primarily filmed in [[Vancouver, British Columbia]], Canada, with location filming in [[Chicago, Illinois]]. ''Batwoman'' follows Kate Kane overcoming her demons and past to become Gotham City's new symbol of hope as the vigilante Batwoman.\n\nIn May 2018, it was announced that Batwoman would appear in \"[[Elseworlds (Arrowverse)|Elseworlds]]\", the Arrowverse series' 2018 crossover, with an announcement two months later that a series centered on the character was in development from Dries. [[Ruby Rose]] was cast in the title role in August of the same year. In January 2019, the series received a pilot order from the CW, to be considered for a series order in the [[2019\u201320 United States network television schedule|2019\u201320 television season]]. The show was picked up to series in May 2019 and in October 2019 a full season of 22 episodes was ordered. In January 2020, The CW renewed the series for a second season.\n\n== Premise ==\nThree years after billionaire philanthropist Bruce Wayne and his vigilante alter ego [[Batman]] disappeared,{{efn|It is stated by Kate Kane in the ''[[Elseworlds (Arrowverse)|Elseworlds]]'' crossover that both Batman and Bruce Wayne have \"gone missing.\"}} his cousin Kate Kane sets out to overcome her demons and become a symbol of hope by protecting the streets of [[Gotham City]] as [[Batwoman]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.digitalspy.com/tv/ustv/a27499099/batwoman-season-1-trailer-arrowverse/ |title=Batwoman trailer reveals origin of Ruby Rose's LGBTQ+ superhero |date=May 16, 2019 |work=Digital Spy |access-date=June 3, 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190603034728/https://www.digitalspy.com/tv/ustv/a27499099/batwoman-season-1-trailer-arrowverse/ |archive-date=June 3, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"BatwomanSeries\" />\n\n== Cast and characters ==\n<!--Can someone split the character section when Season Two begins?-->\n=== Main ===\n<!--Main cast order is according to original broadcasting credits (the pilot episode). Do NOT rearrange cast order, per MOS:TVCAST. In addition, new starring cast members will be at the bottom of the list.-->\n* [[Ruby Rose]] as [[Batwoman|Kate Kane / Batwoman]]: An [[Coming out|out]] [[lesbian]] who, armed with a passion for social justice and a flair for speaking her mind, dedicates herself to defending Gotham in Batman's absence.<ref name=\"BatwomanSeries\" /><ref name=\"RoseCast\" /> Gracyn Shinyei portrays a younger Kate.\n* [[Rachel Skarsten]] as [[Beth Kane|Beth Kane / Alice]]: Kate's presumed-dead twin sister and the leader of the Wonderland Gang whose personality goes from maniacal to charming and back again as she sets out to erode Gotham's sense of security.<ref name=\"Skarsten\" /> Ava Sleeth portrays a younger Beth.\n** Skarsten also portrayed an alternate version of Beth who was displaced from her native Earth during \"Crisis on Infinite Earths\" and appeared on Earth-Prime. This version did not get lost during the car accident. She is later killed by August Cartwright.\n* [[Meagan Tandy]] as [[Sophie Moore]]: A military academy graduate turned high-level Crows agent and Kate's estranged ex-girlfriend who serves as one of Gotham's protectors.<ref name=\"TandyJohnsonKang\" /> \n* Nicole Kang as Mary Hamilton: Kate's stepsister and a medical student/influencer-in-the-making who makes it her mission to provide aid to those living in Gotham's under-served communities.<ref name=\"TandyJohnsonKang\" />\n* Camrus Johnson as [[Luke Fox (character)|Luke Fox]]: A staunch Dark Knight loyalist and the son of [[Lucius Fox]] who keeps [[Wayne Tower]] secure in Batman's absence but understands that Gotham needs a new hero.<ref name=\"TandyJohnsonKang\" />\n** Camrus Johnson also portrays his Earth-99 counterpart.\n* Elizabeth Anweis as Catherine Hamilton-Kane (season 1): Kate's stepmother and one of Gotham's most powerful citizens who made her fortune as a defense contractor and the [[Chief executive officer|CEO]] of Hamilton Dynamics.<ref name=\"Anweis\" /> \n* [[Dougray Scott]] as [[Jacob Kane]]: Kate and Beth's father and a former military colonel with a chip on his shoulder who commands a private security agency, the Crows, in an attempt to protect Gotham better than Batman could.<ref name=\"ScottCastSiegaDirector\" />\n\n[[LaMonica Garrett]] also stars on \"[[Crisis on Infinite Earths (Arrowverse)|Crisis on Infinite Earths: Part Two]]\" as [[Monitor (Arrowverse)|Mar Novu / Monitor]], a multiversal being who tests different Earths in the multiverse in preparation for an impending \"crisis\" orchestrated by his polar opposite, [[Anti-Monitor (Arrowverse)|Mobius / Anti-Monitor]].<ref name=\"BatwomanPressRelease\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/listings/20191121cw03/ |title=(#108) \"Crisis on Infinite Earths: Part Two\" |website=[[The Futon Critic]] |url-status=live |archive-url=http://archive.is/HpwTr |archive-date=November 22, 2019 |access-date=November 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Recurring ===\n<!-- Reliably sourced and/or confirmed to make 4+ appearances in the series -->\n* [[Greyston Holt]] as Tyler: A Crows agent and Sophie's soon to be ex-husband.\n* Brendon Zub as Chuck Dodgson: A former Crows agent who serves as Alice's second-in-command and lover.\n* [[Rachel Maddow]] as the voice of [[Vesper Fairchild]]: A snarky gossip maven and media personality.<ref name=\"RachelMaddow\" />\n* Sam Littlefield as Jonathan \"Johnny\" Cartwright / Mouse: A disfigured man with a talent for voice mimicry and impersonation who considers himself Alice's brother figure.<ref name=\"Littlefield\" /> Nicholas Holmes portrays a younger Johnny.\n* John Emmet Tracy and [[Sebastian Roch\u00e9]] as August Cartwright / Dr. Ethan Campbell: A well-known plastic surgeon and philanthropist.<ref name=\"SebastianRoch\u00e9\" /> Ethan is later revealed to be August Cartwright, Mouse's father who fished Beth out of the river following the accident and imprisoned her for his own nefarious purposes. August is later accidentally killed by Kate.\n\n=== Guest ===\n{{Very long|section|small=left|date=March 2020}}\n* Gray Horse Rider as Kate's trainer: An unnamed man who trained Kate in Siberia at the time when the Wonderland Gang kidnapped Sophie during an attack at the Bat-Signal shutdown event.\n* Chris Shields as Michael Akins: The [[mayor]] of Gotham City.\n* [[Michelle Morgan (actress)|Michelle Morgan]] as Gabrielle \"Gabi\" Kane: The wife of Jacob Kane and mother of Kate and Beth who perished in a car accident that Batman tried to prevent.\n* [[Giles Panton]] as Shane McKillen: A man who works for Catherine. After losing a pinkie to Alice after a failed mission with his fellow men, he carries Alice's message to Catherine and leaves her stating that she is on her own.\n* [[Gabriel Mann]] as [[Hush (character)|Thomas \"Tommy\" Elliot]]: A real estate mogul and former childhood friend of Bruce Wayne who harbors a dark chip on his shoulder that threatens Kate's secret identity.<ref name=\"Hush\">{{Cite web |url=https://tvline.com/2019/10/02/batwoman-photos-gabriel-mann-tommy-elliot-hush-rachel-matthews-magpie/ |title=Batwoman Baddies First Looks: Revenge Fave Gabriel Mann Is Hush, Rachel Matthews Cast as Magpie |last=Matt Webb Mitovich |website=TVLine |language=en |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191002224406/https://tvline.com/2019/10/02/batwoman-photos-gabriel-mann-tommy-elliot-hush-rachel-matthews-magpie/ |archive-date=October 2, 2019 |access-date=October 2, 2019}}</ref>\n* Brianne Howey as Reagan, a bartender and Kate's love interest.\n* Rachel Matthews as [[Magpie (character)|Margaret \"Margot\" Pyle / Magpie]]: An intelligent and deft jewel thief obsessed with shiny things who develops big plans for individuals that take their wealth for granted.<ref name=\"Hush\" />\n* [[Jim Pirri]] as Bertrand Eldon / Executioner: A former [[executioner]] at Blackgate Penitentiary who starts going after the same group of people he blames for sending innocents to [[death row]]. He is killed by Jacob which set off a gas-based fail-safe that nearly killed Batwoman and Jacob. The Executioner is loosely based off the minor Batman villain of the same name.\n* [[Mark Gibbon]] as Angus Stanton: An assistant district attorney who is one of the Executioner's victims.\n* Matthew Graham as Dean Deveraux: A worker at Hamilton Dynamics that Mouse impersonates. He is later killed by Mouse when he gets frustrated at Alice for keeping Batwoman's true identity a secret.\n* Kheon Clarke as Chris \"The Fist\" Medlock: A boxer and ex-con previously prosecuted by Stanton who was suspected of being Executioner.\n* Phillip Mitchell as Stu Donnelly: A GCPD detective who is one of the Executioner's victims.\n* Brent Fidler as Judge Raymond Calverick: A corrupt hanging judge who worked with Angus and Stu to send innocent men to Blackgate Penitentiary's death row.\n* Christina Wolfe as [[Julia Pennyworth]]: A British spy, daughter of [[Alfred Pennyworth]], and an old friend of Bruce and Kate as well as Kate's ex-lover.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/11/11/batwoman-julia-alfred-daughter-photos-teaser/ |title=Batwoman welcomes Alfred's 'crafty' daughter Julia to Gotham in new exclusive photos |last=Agard |first=Chancellor |date=November 11, 2019 |website=Entertainment Weekly |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191112013935/https://ew.com/tv/2019/11/11/batwoman-julia-alfred-daughter-photos-teaser/ |archive-date=November 12, 2019 |access-date=November 11, 2019}}</ref>\n* Garfield Wilson as The Rifle: A professional assassin who works for the mysterious figure known as Safiyah.\n* Cameron McDonald as Jack Forbes: The [[police commissioner]] of the GCPD.\n* [[Kevin Conroy]] as [[Batman franchise media#Bruce Wayne (Earth-99)|Bruce Wayne]] ([[List of DC Multiverse worlds#Arrowverse|Earth-99]]):<ref name=\"CrisisBatwomanHour\">{{Cite web |url=https://tvline.com/gallery/crisis-on-infinite-earths-photos-arrowverse-crossover/ |title='Crisis on Infinite Earths' Arrowverse Crossover Photos |last=Webb Mitovich |first=Matt |date=October 1, 2019 |website=[[TVLine]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191206212248/https://tvline.com/gallery/crisis-on-infinite-earths-photos-arrowverse-crossover/ |archive-date=December 6, 2019 |access-date=November 20, 2019}}</ref> An older parallel universe counterpart of Bruce Wayne from the future of Earth-99, who's confined to an exo-skeleton after killing his world's Superman. He lost all hope sometime during his career and started killing his enemies, which was made worse when his Kate died trying to show him the error of his ways. Bruce was accidentally electrocuted during a scuffle with Kate of Earth-1 and Kara.\n* Malia Pyles as Parker Torres: A lesbian student at Gotham Prep and adept hacker. After an ex-girlfriend of hers outed her, she staged a train brake failure while she was a passenger to garner sympathy from her homophobic parents. Later, she anonymously extorted all of Gotham under the threat of doxxing in order to gain money to leave the city and start a new life. After her life was threatened by Alice, Parker secretly sent a text to everyone that Alice and a bomb were at Gotham Prep under the cover that she'd leak Batwoman's identity. With the lives saved and Alice in Crows custody, Kate made Parker a deal to do community service and return any extortion money instead of going to juvenile detention, while supporting her out lifestyle.\n* Kurt Szarka as [[Slam Bradley]]: A member of the Gotham City Police Department. After he saved Batwoman from being hit by a loose grappling hook, the media and many Gotham citizens began \"[[Shipping (fandom)|shipping]]\" them, to Kate's chagrin.\n* Seth Whittaker as Reggie Harris: A tough inmate at Blackgate Penitentiary that Jacob encounters and was said to have been the one who killed Lucius Fox. After his re-trial was accepted following Executioner's attacks, Reggie was confronted by Luke outside his grandmother's home. He did talk with Lucius before the events that led to his frame-up and is then shot by an unseen hitman in front of Luke.\n* Ryan Rosery as Bryan Akins: The son of Mayor Akins.\n* Gage Marsh as Steven Forbes: The son of Commissioner Forbes.\n* [[Kayla Ewell]] as [[Nocturna (DC Comics)|Natalia Knight / Nocturna]]: A woman with [[porphyria]] who adopts a vampire persona and targets people for their blood while using [[ketamine]] in fanged dental implants to stun them.\n* [[Alessandra Torresani]] as [[Duela Dent]]: The niece of [[Two-Face|Harvey Dent]] who slashed her own face when she was young and targeted social media influencers. After being apprehended, Alice stole her face so she could use it to get revenge on August.\n* [[Jeryl Prescott]] as Diane Moore: The mother of Sophie.\n* [[Debra Mooney]] as Mabel Cartwright: The mother of August and the grandmother of Mouse. She is killed by Beth/Alice after she found her mother's severed head in a locked fridge in August's cabin.\n\n== Episodes ==\n{{Episode table |background=#762C2A |overall= |title= |director= |writer= |airdate= |prodcode= |viewers= |country=U.S. |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 1\n |Title           = Pilot\n |DirectedBy      = [[Marcos Siega]]\n |WrittenBy       = [[Caroline Dries]]\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|10|6}}\n |ProdCode        = T15.10154\n |Viewers         = 1.86<ref name=\"1.01\">{{Cite web |url=https://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/daily-ratings/sunday-final-ratings-oct-6-2019/ |title='Sunday Night Football' adjusts up, 'The Simpsons,' 'Bless the Harts,' and others adjust down: Sunday final ratings |last=Welch |first=Alex |date=October 8, 2019 |website=[[TV by the Numbers]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191008145733/https://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/daily-ratings/sunday-final-ratings-oct-6-2019/ |archive-date=October 8, 2019 |access-date=October 8, 2019}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary    = Three years after the disappearance of [[Gotham City]]-based vigilante [[Batman]], [[Jacob Kane]] and his private security firm the Crows preside over a gala led by Mayor Michael Akins to turn off the [[Bat-Signal]]. At the height of the festivities, [[Beth Kane|Alice]] and the Wonderland Gang crash the event and abduct operative [[Sophie Moore]], prompting Kane's stepdaughter Mary to call his biological daughter [[Batwoman|Kate]]. Returning from overseas, Kate learns Alice is targeting her father and sets out to locate her cousin, billionaire Bruce Wayne. She discovers, however, that Bruce is Batman, who she blamed for failing to save her sister and mother after they died in a car crash. Realizing there's more to the story, she dons her cousin's [[Batsuit]], altered by [[Wayne Enterprises]] employee [[Luke Fox (character)|Luke Fox]], before rescuing Sophie and foiling Alice's plan to detonate a bomb in a crowded park. The next day, as the news reports on what they believe is Batman's return, Kate begins to suspect Alice is her sister.\n |LineColor       = 762C2A\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 2\n |Title           = The Rabbit Hole\n |DirectedBy      = Marcos Siega\n |WrittenBy       = Caroline Dries\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|10|13}}\n |ProdCode        = T13.21952\n |Viewers         = 1.45<ref name=\"1.02\">{{Cite web |url=https://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/daily-ratings/sunday-final-ratings-oct-13-2019/ |title='Kids Say the Darndest Things, 'Sunday Night Football' adjust up, 'Shark Tank' adjusts down: Sunday final ratings |last=Welch |first=Alex |date=October 15, 2019 |website=TV by the Numbers |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191015152838/https://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/daily-ratings/sunday-final-ratings-oct-13-2019/ |archive-date=October 15, 2019 |access-date=October 15, 2019}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary    = Kate's growing suspicions that Beth is Alice drive a wedge between her and Jacob, who firmly believes Beth is dead based on the evidence. While trying to get Alice's favorite knife which she stole tested for DNA, she comes under attack from a group of thugs that manage to steal it back. Deducing one of Alice's injured men used Mary's secret clinic, Kate frees him to give Alice a message. Kate then asks Sophie to buy her time while she meets with Alice, who refuses to directly admit she is Beth, but agrees to provide a DNA sample. Sophie tells Jacob where to find them, resulting in Alice being transported to [[Arkham Asylum]]. Alice then reveals to Kate she tasked her boyfriend, ex-Crows agent Dodgson, with killing Mary; which prompts Kate to save her before rescuing Alice from a bomb intended to kill her before both Kate and Alice escape from the police. Meanwhile, Kate's stepmother Catherine orders the thugs she tasked with stealing Alice's knife to destroy it. After 